NAME
       read - read from a file descriptor

SYNOPSIS
       #include <unistd.h>

       ssize_t read(int fd, void *buf, size_t count);

DESCRIPTION
       Attempts to read up to count bytes from file descriptor fd into
       the buffer pointed to by buf. The return value is the number of
       bytes actually transferred, or -1 on error with errno set.

       For block devices the offset advances by the number of bytes
       read; for terminals see TTY MODES below.

TTY MODES
       /dev/tty respects the termios c_lflag bits ICANON, ECHO, ISIG.
       In canonical mode read returns whole lines terminated by '\\n'.
       In non-canonical (raw) mode every byte is delivered as soon as
       it arrives.

       Non-blocking reads on the TTY are activated through the
       TIOCSNONBLOCK ioctl with a non-zero int argument. When set, read
       returns -1 with errno = EAGAIN if no input is ready.

RETURN VALUE
       Number of bytes read. 0 indicates end of file. -1 indicates an
       error and errno is set.

ERRORS
       EAGAIN     non-blocking and no data available
       EBADF      fd is not open for reading
       EINTR      interrupted by a signal
       EFAULT     buf is not a valid pointer

SEE ALSO
       write(2), open(2), ioctl(2)
